Understand the importance of sleep.

19
00:01:29,319 --> 00:01:31,299
And Temper is a mattress like no other.

20
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:32,200
NASA approved.

21
00:01:32,560 --> 00:01:33,840
It's the world's best in bedding.

22
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:35,159
Have a look at Temper today.

23
00:01:36,980 --> 00:01:44,780
Michael Whipper Whipfley is a multi-award winning radio presenter and comedian who has used his microphone for good over many years.

24
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:55,540
Supporting and raising thousands of dollars for youth-related charities across Australia, including Ronald McDonald House, Little Wings Flight Service, Cooper Rich Braiding Foundation for sarcoma research,

25
00:01:56,120 --> 00:01:57,260
and BATTA for youth mental health.

26
00:01:57,299 --> 00:01:58,299
To name a few.

27
00:01:58,959 --> 00:02:06,459
Whipper has launched a campaign to change legislation to increase the age when children are legally able to use social media from 13 to 16.

28
00:02:07,019 --> 00:02:11,300
He partnered with Finch CEO Rob Galuzzo to create the initiative 36 Months.

29
00:02:12,120 --> 00:02:21,199
And he's using the platform of his radio show, which has already seen the campaign receive verbal support from the New South Wales Premier Chris Minns and the Prime Minister Anthony Albanese.

30
00:02:21,340 --> 00:02:25,219
Whipper, I've been a great admirer and fan of yours for a long period of time.

31
00:02:25,219 --> 00:02:27,139
Congratulations on all that you're doing.

32
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:28,219
Thanks, Duff.

33
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:29,659
We're having a swing, mate.

34
00:02:29,780 --> 00:02:31,060
I mean, there's no other way to do it.

35
00:02:31,099 --> 00:02:35,300
You've done a lot of breakfast shows as well, so a lot of years behind the microphone.

36
00:02:35,479 --> 00:02:47,379
So you do have moments between sort of running competitions like Beat the Bomb and The Fugitive and giving away Taylor Swift tickets where you think, hang on a minute, this thing talks to all these people.

37
00:02:47,780 --> 00:02:48,819
What can we do with it?

38
00:02:48,819 --> 00:02:56,259
What should we be doing with this thing outside of what's your favourite Chinese dish and should there be pineapple on pizza?

39
00:02:56,259 --> 00:02:58,240
You've done them all, Duff.

40
00:02:58,340 --> 00:02:59,180
You've done them all.

41
00:03:00,139 --> 00:03:02,139
I want to say 1-3-3-3-5-3.

42
00:03:02,240 --> 00:03:06,699
Give us a call when you said, oh, I've got a bit of muscle memory back, Whipper.

43
00:03:07,240 --> 00:03:10,919
But in fairness to you, mate, not everyone thinks the way you do.

44
00:03:11,039 --> 00:03:12,539
People think this is a great gig.

45
00:03:12,620 --> 00:03:13,639
You get paid well.

46
00:03:14,199 --> 00:03:22,319
You and Fitzy, you know, you work with great people and Kate Ritchie's joined your show and you get free stuff and you're home three hours later and life's good.

47
00:03:22,319 --> 00:03:25,020
Not everyone's got a social conscience like you.

48
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:26,240
Has that always been?

49
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:30,240
Has it always been part of the way you've been or is it something you felt the responsibility of?

50
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:33,159
Great question because I do think about this a little bit.

51
00:03:33,319 --> 00:03:54,879
And I think, as you know, in this job and when you're in the media or any level of celebrity, I suppose, you kind of become the more your profile grows, the more demand there is for you to be involved in different things, different organisations, be it a charity or a favour to help out or emceeing an event to raise money.

52
00:03:54,879 --> 00:04:03,879
And you kind of, I suppose, you're exposed to more things, you're exposed to more stories, you're exposed to the organisations that might need a little bit of help.

53
00:04:04,300 --> 00:04:13,439
And when you seize and hear about some things that go on, I think it comes with the charity as well and becoming a parent, you sit back and think, well, what can I do?

54
00:04:13,740 --> 00:04:14,960
Because that doesn't seem right.

55
00:04:15,020 --> 00:04:16,500
So how can I get involved?

56
00:04:16,980 --> 00:04:23,660
And I think as we all grow up, we sort of seek more in our life than just the output of what we do on a daily basis.

57
00:04:23,660 --> 00:04:24,759
It's that question of what?

58
00:04:24,759 --> 00:04:25,899
What else can we do?

59
00:04:26,560 --> 00:04:40,060
When you think about the audience that we have out there and then you look at some of the things that go on and at the same time, Darcy, you'd know through radio, you're very lucky to meet a lot of people and your circle widens very quickly.

60
00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:41,779
You would have known that through footy as well.

61
00:04:42,199 --> 00:04:52,779
So all of a sudden you've got this handful of great people that are in powerful positions or with great profile and then you stumble across a need that desires and requires a change.

62
00:04:52,819 --> 00:04:54,720
And you think, hang on, I've got all these pieces.

63
00:04:54,759 --> 00:04:58,540
If I bought them all in, we might be able to do something really special here.

64
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:00,439
I think that's what we've landed on here.

65
00:05:00,839 --> 00:05:03,199
And again, I've got so much admiration for you, Whipper.

66
00:05:03,540 --> 00:05:09,779
Not many people can get the prime minister to come into their studio and the premier of your state and then actually launch a campaign.

67
00:05:10,060 --> 00:05:17,319
And is this in part, I mean, you've been really open yourself about having some mental health struggles and reading more of that.

68
00:05:17,439 --> 00:05:19,180
I didn't quite understand the gravitas.

69
00:05:19,180 --> 00:05:24,639
I think you've shared that almost to the point staring at a balcony and looking at potentially ending it.

70
00:05:24,759 --> 00:05:32,899
Has that driven this purpose for you around wanting to make a difference, given the nature of how bad the issues with social media are?

71
00:05:32,959 --> 00:05:35,699
Can you share with us a bit of your background and what got you to that point?

72
00:05:36,180 --> 00:05:40,360
Yeah, I mean, I was doing it tough and I think it was a process of growing up.

73
00:05:40,459 --> 00:05:45,180
There'd been sort of a trigger pulled through personal life, which sort of sent me spiralling.

74
00:05:45,180 --> 00:05:50,139
But I got to a point where it was extremely scary to be there.

75
00:05:50,459 --> 00:05:53,519
And I think you kind of dip your toe in that.

76
00:05:53,639 --> 00:05:54,680
And when you realise we...

77
00:05:54,759 --> 00:06:02,060
When you're out at that moment in time, if you're lucky enough to come back and, you know, hopefully you've got a good team around you, if you find yourself in that position.

78
00:06:02,199 --> 00:06:06,839
And there's obviously a lot of services you can call if you do find yourself there.

79
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:15,120
But I think that plays a part in it because I think about other people that might be in that situation where they think, you know, what would it be easier if I'm not here?

80
00:06:15,420 --> 00:06:20,660
Well, there's a hell of a lot of people around you saying that's the wrong way of thinking.

81
00:06:21,199 --> 00:06:22,220
That's where you've ended up.

82
00:06:22,300 --> 00:06:24,160
But you need it and you want it and you're loved.

83
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:25,279
So you must be here.

84
00:06:25,279 --> 00:06:27,279
So when I think about people that possibly...

85
00:06:28,139 --> 00:06:33,519
And through a lot of adolescent brains and social media influence, kids are finding themselves in that position.

86
00:06:33,980 --> 00:06:39,319
And, you know, I'm not dramatic by saying kids are killing themselves because that can be the result.

87
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:49,360
So it does make me very, very aware and I'm very conscious of the mindset some of those kids might find themselves in.

88
00:06:49,519 --> 00:06:52,779
And that scares me like it scared me back in the day.

89
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:53,779
And with Birgit.

90
00:06:54,160 --> 00:07:05,600
I use admiration because, you know, you're maybe a generation slightly behind me, but we weren't necessarily courageous enough to share those things the way that you have done so openly.

91
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:15,579
And that allows when you see Whipper, he's got this great life and he's living the rock star life and he's funny and everything's going great to say, hey, I could get to that place.

92
00:07:15,759 --> 00:07:20,839
And it doesn't discriminate for you to be able to use your profile again to courageously share that.

93
00:07:20,920 --> 00:07:23,579
Was that a hard thing to do or did it take you a while to get there?

94
00:07:24,160 --> 00:07:24,800
Yeah, it did.

95
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:35,199
It took me a long time, to be honest, because I think you're always once you've had sort of that experience and you've found yourself pretty low, you're always processing it.

96
00:07:35,480 --> 00:07:39,100
I think you're always looking back on it and trying to understand how you ended up there.

97
00:07:39,379 --> 00:07:42,120
But at the same time, you're looking for education.

98
00:07:42,120 --> 00:07:48,759
So you know that if you found yourself heading down that path again, what sort of things can you do?

99
00:07:48,759 --> 00:07:53,699
And I've had moments since then where I've started to feel like that.

100
00:07:54,160 --> 00:07:57,720
And I bring in a routine which helps pull me out of that.

101
00:07:58,319 --> 00:08:02,759
It's not always going to be the solution for every position that I find myself in or for other people.

102
00:08:03,139 --> 00:08:05,199
But it's going back to basics.

103
00:08:05,399 --> 00:08:06,759
It's exercise every day.

104
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:08,439
Exercise is unbelievable.

105
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:12,079
And you don't need to be doing some sort of preseason workout.

106
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:18,720
You can just go for a walk, get off the grog, plenty of water and just get the basics right.

107
00:08:18,720 --> 00:08:24,139
And consider all the little things that you've done that day, which are the basics.

108
00:08:24,300 --> 00:08:27,600
To be big wins, they're success stories in your day.

109
00:08:27,980 --> 00:08:34,620
So the fact that you managed to get yourself out of bed and have a shower that day and maybe you didn't the day before, that is a win.

110
00:08:34,620 --> 00:08:36,639
Write that down as a successful move.

111
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:44,799
And each day it's like lying, it was described to me once like lying in water, where every now and then you lift your head out of the water and you take a breath and you go back down.

112
00:08:44,980 --> 00:08:50,919
And then the next day you take two breaths out of the water and all of a sudden you don't want to be in the water anymore and you can pull yourself out of that.

113
00:08:51,279 --> 00:08:53,679
And I encourage anybody that might find themselves in that position.

114
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:56,159
Just to get back to the basics.

115
00:08:56,419 --> 00:08:59,980
Make sure you walk, water, sleep, do the basics.

116
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:01,659
That advice, Whipper, isn't it?

117
00:09:01,659 --> 00:09:07,419
I think anyone, it's a spectrum, isn't it, for all of us around having some degree of mental health.

118
00:09:07,659 --> 00:09:09,759
It's a continuum, isn't it?

119
00:09:09,820 --> 00:09:19,899
And all of us, someone said to me once, you know, you go and take a truckload of drugs, don't sleep for three and a half days, and then you're a chance to be almost at the end.

120
00:09:19,899 --> 00:09:23,159
Life is this thin wedge.

121
00:09:23,159 --> 00:09:25,379
And we're all dancing on the edge of it.

122
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:28,559
As you said, you get up, you do your morning routine, you exercise, you drink water, you eat.

123
00:09:28,639 --> 00:09:34,039
You feel bulletproof, but you can let that go without even understanding it, can't you?

124
00:09:34,179 --> 00:09:35,100
And suddenly you feel yourself.

125
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:36,059
It slides really quickly.

126
00:09:36,379 --> 00:09:37,059
Amazing, isn't it?

127
00:09:37,519 --> 00:09:38,340
Yeah, but you know what?

128
00:09:38,460 --> 00:09:49,500
The other part of me coming out and talking about it too was when I saw more and more people, the reaction I would get, I mean, to see Paul Gallen come out and talk about his battle.

129
00:09:49,500 --> 00:09:52,519
And I thought, Paul Gallen, that guy's tough as nails.

130
00:09:52,519 --> 00:09:55,500
You know, there's no weakness in talking about that.

131
00:09:55,879 --> 00:10:04,480
So every time I would see somebody that I admired or looked up to, a professional in the field talk about it, I suppose I reacted by how it made me feel.

132
00:10:04,879 --> 00:10:12,559
And me telling my story is the hope that I could get that reaction from somebody else that might be listening that possibly enjoys the radio show.

133
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:16,879
And we're in the midst of what is irrefutably a mental health crisis.

134
00:10:16,879 --> 00:10:21,940
And now it's irrefutably linked to the perils of social media for our youth.

135
00:10:21,940 --> 00:10:22,080
Yeah.

136
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:22,100
Yeah.

137
00:10:22,100 --> 00:10:22,120
Yeah.

138
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:22,159
Yeah.

139
00:10:22,159 --> 00:10:22,220
Yeah.

140
00:10:22,220 --> 00:10:22,240
Yeah.

141
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:22,259
Yeah.

142
00:10:22,259 --> 00:10:22,500
Yeah.

143
00:10:22,519 --> 00:10:27,080
Unbelievable spikes in eating disorders, particularly in young teenage girls.

144
00:10:27,220 --> 00:10:28,460
Some of the stats are horrific.

145
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:34,340
Anxiety, depression, self-harm and suicide in Australia and around the globe are at record levels.

146
00:10:34,860 --> 00:10:41,759
The link is directly to the algorithms that our kids look at on their phones, the unrealistic imagery that's there.

147
00:10:42,299 --> 00:10:46,220
How big a problem is it from the work that you've done to research it?

148
00:10:46,759 --> 00:10:50,940
You know, I was talking to a dad last night and the plan was to get him on the radio show.

149
00:10:51,179 --> 00:10:52,240
And we didn't because it just didn't work.

150
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:53,440
Because it just didn't feel right.

151
00:10:53,740 --> 00:10:59,700
Because it was just, it was far too, far too confronting what he's had to go through.

152
00:10:59,820 --> 00:11:04,740
He lost his daughter through the online bullying he received through one of the social media platforms.

153
00:11:05,559 --> 00:11:09,940
And he said he lives every day now as if he is numb.

154
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:11,879
He says he has a son.

155
00:11:11,980 --> 00:11:13,539
So he said, I have something to live for.

156
00:11:13,539 --> 00:11:20,340
But at the same time, I'm completely numb and there is nothing that brings him happiness.

157
00:11:20,860 --> 00:11:22,120
I mean, that's from the dad's point.

158
00:11:22,240 --> 00:11:37,259
What scares me even more is to think of the mindset and the feeling that his daughter must have had and how long it went on for and how long it took for her to come to a point where she felt she was in a situation where there was no way back.

159
00:11:37,940 --> 00:11:46,639
And since putting my hand up, and as I've said, Darsen, why I'm so grateful for coming on the show, like you, I'm saying we've got a problem here, guys.

160
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:49,039
So I'm representing the parents and the teachers.

161
00:11:49,799 --> 00:11:52,139
I'm representing anybody that thinks this simply.

162
00:11:52,240 --> 00:11:53,360
It doesn't make sense.

163
00:11:53,799 --> 00:11:57,519
Imagine if there was another product out there, Darsen, call it a bloody shampoo.

164
00:11:58,580 --> 00:12:06,759
And one out of two kids that used the shampoo ended up with some sort of psychological impact, anxiety or depression.

165
00:12:07,179 --> 00:12:11,799
But in extreme cases, if you kept using the shampoo, you could end up dead.

166
00:12:12,220 --> 00:12:16,059
Well, that product wouldn't be on the store for more than five seconds.

167
00:12:16,059 --> 00:12:17,080
That would be gone.

168
00:12:17,539 --> 00:12:18,759
And that's what we're dealing with.

169
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:20,740
And nobody is putting a stop to it.

170
00:12:21,259 --> 00:12:22,220
And I just don't.

171
00:12:22,240 --> 00:12:23,159
I don't understand it.

172
00:12:23,519 --> 00:12:30,259
And, you know, from a parent's point of view, Darsen, with three kids, as you know, you want to be able to parent.

173
00:12:30,519 --> 00:12:43,700
And the parents are being stripped of having any impact or involvement or being able to advise or even prepare and arm their kids with any skills because the greatest influence is coming from some smart algorithm.

174
00:12:44,019 --> 00:12:45,139
It's crazy, isn't it?

175
00:12:45,179 --> 00:12:46,820
I mean, the data's next level.

176
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:51,059
70% of teens have had a negative experience online in the last week.

177
00:12:51,139 --> 00:12:52,220
One in three have been exposed.

178
00:12:52,240 --> 00:12:54,960
Two disturbing or traumatic content.

179
00:12:55,100 --> 00:12:58,399
One in four have been cyber bullied or sexually harassed in social media.

180
00:12:59,039 --> 00:13:03,980
You've really drilled into something that seems like a no-brainer, doesn't it?

181
00:13:04,059 --> 00:13:05,299
Raising the age limit.

182
00:13:05,759 --> 00:13:08,200
It's not a hard thing from 13 to 16.

183
00:13:08,480 --> 00:13:10,379
So the campaign's called 36 Months.

184
00:13:10,720 --> 00:13:15,679
Can you tell us why you're focused in on that and why those 36 months count so much?

185
00:13:15,899 --> 00:13:17,539
I'm not trying to stop Instagram.

186
00:13:17,919 --> 00:13:21,539
I'm saying that the impact on adolescent brains between 13...

187
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:37,019
...and 16, or even younger if we can, but my understanding of the platform as far as the law goes here in Australia, and it's a law that's sort of extended from America under their Parental Act from 1998, says that if you're 13, you can land on one of these platforms.

188
00:13:37,019 --> 00:13:42,919
So, yes, the 36 months is that adolescent brain period of development.

189
00:13:43,019 --> 00:13:46,200
And, you know, if I had it my way, it'd be 18.

190
00:13:46,460 --> 00:13:48,899
But, you know, that might be a stretch too far.

191
00:13:49,299 --> 00:13:52,139
So the other thing with the 36 months is...

192
00:13:52,240 --> 00:14:10,440
You've got to think, if we can give that back to the kids and families can reconnect, imagine the teaching and the skills we can put in place over those three years, three crucial years, so when a kid reaches the age of 16 and decides they want to be on social media, that they have the skills to handle what might be thrown at them.

193
00:14:10,440 --> 00:14:16,399
So the curriculum around what can be built in to the 36 months is exciting to think about.

194
00:14:16,879 --> 00:14:19,139
You know, you can come back to the family.

195
00:14:19,740 --> 00:14:21,440
You know, one of the taglines we've been using, Darcy, is...

196
00:14:22,240 --> 00:14:26,399
You know, 36 months to get to know yourself before the rest of the world does.

197
00:14:27,100 --> 00:14:29,600
You know, who knows who they are at the age of 13?

198
00:14:30,860 --> 00:14:31,759
It's madness.

199
00:14:32,519 --> 00:14:33,679
It's insane, isn't it?

200
00:14:33,679 --> 00:14:38,179
You know, as a father of four, it's the biggest issue that you think about every day.

201
00:14:38,240 --> 00:14:45,399
And I'm sure you're in that same bracket of just this new territory that no one really understood previously.

202
00:14:45,399 --> 00:14:48,559
But now you understand what these platforms are doing.

203
00:14:48,639 --> 00:14:49,679
There's a great book.

204
00:14:50,340 --> 00:14:52,220
Johan Hari wrote a book about stolen folk.

205
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:54,980
And, you know, at the extreme end, we're losing kids to suicide.

206
00:14:54,980 --> 00:14:56,179
And that's happening daily.

207
00:14:56,340 --> 00:15:00,340
